				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${{\rm{SWMT}}}({\sigma }_{2})=\frac{1}{\Delta {\upsigma }_{2}}\iint {BdA}$$\end{document}SWMT(σ2)=1Δσ2∬BdAwhere B is the surface density flux (in units of kg seawater m−2 s−1, defined as positive for ocean density increase), σ2 is the density referenced to 2000-m depth (in units of kg m−3, after subtracting 1000 kg m−3), dA is the surface outcrop area (in units of m2, corresponding to densities in the range from σ2-Δσ2/2 to σ2 + Δσ2/2). The unit of SWMT is converted from m3 s−1 to Sv (1 Sv = 106 m3 s−1) in the paper. The density flux comprises heat and salt fluxes that referred to as Bheat and Bsalt, respectively. The heat flux is3\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
